explanation: OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro) - The call in the target function is via this macro; its expansion may call other helpers or perform comparisons (possibly using memcmp) so the macro definition must be inspected. OS_impl_mutex_table (table variable) - The table implementation being indexed may contain comparison logic (e.g. searching entries) that could call memcmp on stored keys/strings. OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (function) - This helper is the likely implementation of token→index mapping (appears in the static graph) and could perform memcmp on token contents; its body must be checked. OS_object_token_t (type) - The token is dereferenced and passed into the table/macro; its layout (e.g. containing char* name or fixed char[] ) determines whether any comparisons would be against null-terminated strings. OS_impl_mutex_internal_record_t (struct) - Needed to know the types of members (impl->id) and ensure no hidden string operations occur in accessing the record. pthread_mutex_unlock (function) and pthread_mutex_t (type) - Declaration/type are required to confirm that the only operation performed here is a mutex unlock and that no string comparisons occur as part of that call. OS_SEM_FAILURE and OS_SUCCESS (macros/enum values) - Included to fully understand return semantics (not likely to involve memcmp but necessary for complete analysis). memcmp (standard function) - The symbol under the MISRA rule; search occurrences in the above macros/functions/types to determine if memcmp is used to compare null-terminated strings.
